<header>
  <h1>🧰 Anycubic Kobra S1 — Complete Maintenance Guide</h1>
  <p>Keep your printer running smooth · Step-by-step · Visual checklists</p>
</header>

<!-- ═══ SCHEDULE ═══ -->
<section>
  <div class="card">
    <h2>📅 Quick-Reference Schedule</h2>
    <table class="schedule">
      <tr><th>Interval</th><th>Task</th><th>See §</th></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Every print</strong></td><td>Wipe spring steel sheet; check first layer</td><td>9</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Weekly</strong></td><td>Inspect fans for dust; check camera lens</td><td>8, 4</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Monthly</strong></td><td>Clean &amp; inspect Y-axis linear rods</td><td>2</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Every 3 months</strong></td><td>Lubricate Z-axis lead screw</td><td>1</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Every 3–5 spools</strong></td><td>Inspect cutter assembly for wear</td><td>5</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>As needed</strong></td><td>Nozzle cleaning / cold pull; replace silicone sock</td><td>6, 7</td></tr>
    </table>
    <p class="alert alert-info">🔗 Original source: <a href="https://wiki.anycubic.com/en/fdm-3d-printer/kobra-s1-combo/maintenance-recommendations" target="_blank">Anycubic Wiki — Kobra S1 Maintenance Recommendations</a></p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- ═══ SAFETY ═══ -->
<section>
  <div class="card">
    <h2>⚠️ Safety First</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Always power off and disconnect</strong> the printer before cleaning or touching moving parts (Z-screw lubrication is the one exception — motor must be on to move axes).</li>
      <li>Let the hotend cool below 40 °C before handling the nozzle or silicone sock.</li>
      <li>Use insulated gloves when cleaning a heated nozzle.</li>
      <li>Work in a well-ventilated area if using isopropyl alcohol or compressed air.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- ═══ 1. Z-AXIS LEAD SCREW ═══ -->
<section>
  <div class="card">
    <h2>1. Z-Axis Lead Screw <span class="badge">Every 3 months</span></h2>

    <p><strong>Symptoms it needs attention:</strong> Grinding, clicking, or uneven noise when the Z-axis moves. (Tip: printing above 350 mm/s produces normal metal friction sounds — don’t confuse the two.)</p>

    <h3>🛠 Step-by-Step</h3>
    <ol>
      <li><span class="step-num">1</span> <strong>Clean the screw.</strong> With printer off, wipe the lead screw with a lint-free cloth to remove dust and old grease. A soft brush helps reach the threads.</li>
      <li><span class="step-num">2</span> <strong>Zero the Z axis.</strong> Power on → <em>Tools → Move → All Zero</em> (or <em>Z Zero</em>). The bed rises to the top.</li>
      <li><span class="step-num">3</span> <strong>Apply grease.</strong> Dab a <strong>pea-sized</strong> amount of PTFE-based grease (e.g. Super Lube 21030) onto a clean cloth. Run it along the exposed screw threads. Avoid lithium grease — it runs off.</li>
      <li><span class="step-num">4</span> <strong>Spread evenly.</strong> Press <em>Z+</em> to lower the bed to the bottom, then apply grease to the remaining threads. Hit <em>Z Zero</em> to raise again — the nut spreads the grease naturally.</li>
      <li><span class="step-num">5</span> <strong>Test.</strong> Run a short print or move the Z-axis through its full range. Listen for smooth, quiet travel.</li>
    </ol>

    <div class="alert alert-warn">
      <strong>⚠️ Do not use liquid oil.</strong> It drips off the screw and misses the nut, making the problem worse.
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- ═══ 2. Y-AXIS LINEAR RODS ═══ -->
<section>
  <div class="card">
    <h2>2. Y-Axis Linear Rods <span class="badge">Monthly</span></h2>
    <p>The Y-axis glides on steel linear rods through linear bearings. Dust or filament fragments can cause binding and layer inconsistencies.</p>

    <h3>🛠 Step-by-Step</h3>
    <ol>
      <li><span class="step-num">1</span> <strong>Power off &amp; unplug.</strong></li>
      <li><span class="step-num">2</span> <strong>Inspect.</strong> Gently slide the bed by hand. Feel for roughness, catches, or visible debris on the rods. Use a lint-free cloth or soft brush to wipe away dust.</li>
      <li><span class="step-num">3</span> <strong>Blow clean.</strong> If debris is stubborn, use an air gun, blower, or compressed air can — <strong>short, gentle bursts</strong> to avoid blowing dust into electronics.</li>
      <li><span class="step-num">4</span> <strong>Lubricate.</strong> Apply a <strong>thin, even coat</strong> of PTFE grease along the rod surface. Slide the bed back and forth by hand to work it in.</li>
      <li><span class="step-num">5</span> <strong>Test.</strong> Reconnect power, home the Y-axis, and run a small print. Listen for smooth, quiet operation.</li>
    </ol>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- ═══ 3. X-AXIS RODS ═══ -->
<section>
  <div class="card">
    <h2>3. X-Axis Rods <span class="badge">As needed</span></h2>
    <p>The X-axis uses <strong>graphene-bearing sleeves</strong> — they are self-lubricating.</p>

    <div class="alert alert-danger"><strong>🚫 NEVER apply grease to the X-axis rods.</strong> Graphene sleeves already provide lubrication; adding grease attracts dust and causes premature wear.</div>

    <h3>🛠 Cleaning</h3>
    <ol>
      <li>Power off and unplug.</li>
      <li>Dampen a lint-free cloth with <strong>isopropyl alcohol</strong> (≥90 %).</li>
      <li>Wipe the rod thoroughly to remove dust, filament dust, and old residue.</li>
      <li>Let the alcohol evaporate completely before powering on.</li>
    </ol>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- ═══ 4. CAMERA ═══ -->
<section>
  <div class="card">
    <h2>4. Camera <span class="badge">As needed / weekly check</span></h2>
    <p>Blurry or hazy time-lapse / monitoring footage usually means a dirty lens.</p>
    <ol>
      <li>Use a <strong>lint-free microfiber cloth</strong> or a cotton swab.</li>
      <li>Lightly moisten with isopropyl alcohol.</li>
      <li>Gently wipe the lens in a circular motion. Avoid pressing hard.</li>
    </ol>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- ═══ 5. CUTTER ASSEMBLY ═══ -->
<section>
  <div class="card">
    <h2>5. Cutter (Filament Cutter) <span class="badge">Every 3–5 spools</span></h2>
    <p>The ACE Pro / filament cutter can dull over time, leading to ragged cuts or failed retractions.</p>
    <ol>
      <li>Power off.</li>
      <li>Use a <strong>S2.0 hex (Allen) key</strong> to remove the cutter assembly.</li>
      <li>Inspect the blade edge. If it’s chipped, rounded, or visibly worn, replace it.</li>
      <li>Reassemble and test with a filament load/unload cycle.</li>
    </ol>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- ═══ 6. HOTEND & NOZZLE ═══ -->
<section>
  <div class="card">
    <h2>6. Hotend &amp; Nozzle <span class="badge">As needed</span></h2>
    <p><strong>Signs of trouble:</strong> under-extrusion, stringing, blobs, clicking extruder, or poor surface finish.</p>

    <h3>🛠 Basic Cleaning (surface gunk)</h3>
    <ol>
      <li>Remove the silicone sock (carefully — it’s brittle when cold).</li>
      <li>Heat nozzle to <strong>200 °C</strong>.</li>
      <li>Wearing insulated gloves, use a paper towel or tweezers to wipe the outside of the nozzle clean.</li>
    </ol>

    <h3>🛠 Deep Clean — Cold Pull (recommended for clogs)</h3>
    <ol>
      <li>Heat hotend to printing temperature for your current filament. Purge a small amount.</li>
      <li>Let it cool to <strong>~90–100 °C</strong> (just above the glass-transition temp of PLA).</li>
      <li>Manually push filament through until it exits the nozzle, then firmly <strong>pull it out</strong> — the tip should come out as a clean plug with debris inside.</li>
      <li>Repeat until the plug comes out clean. Use <strong>nylon cleaning filament</strong> for stubborn clogs (follow the same method).</li>
    </ol>

    <h3>🛠 Clogged Nozzle — Needle Clear</h3>
    <ol>
      <li>Heat nozzle to <strong>230 °C</strong>.</li>
      <li>Carefully insert the provided steel needle (or 0.35 mm nozzle-clearing pin) up into the nozzle orifice.</li>
      <li>Purge filament to push out the dislodged debris.</li>
    </ol>

    <div class="alert alert-warn">
      ⏱ Let the hotend cool down before putting the silicone sock back on.
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- ═══ 7. SILICONE SOCK ═══ -->
<section>
  <div class="card">
    <h2>7. Silicone Sock <span class="badge">Inspect regularly</span></h2>
    <p>The silicone sock insulates the heater block and prevents filament from sticking to it.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Check for:</strong> cracks, tears, or heavy buildup of burnt plastic.</li>
      <li><strong>Replace</strong> if damaged — a torn sock causes temperature instability and stringing.</li>
      <li>Soak a damaged sock in isopropyl alcohol to soften residue, then rinse and dry — but replacement is cheap and recommended.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- ═══ 8. FANS ═══ -->
<section>
  <div class="card">
    <h2>8. Fans (Hotend, Front Cover &amp; Auxiliary) <span class="badge">Weekly check</span></h2>
    <p>Dust buildup on fan blades reduces cooling efficiency and can cause noise or vibration.</p>
    <ol>
      <li>Power off and unplug.</li>
      <li>Use compressed air, a soft brush, or a cotton swab to dislodge dust from blades.</li>
      <li>For stubborn grime, dampen a swab with <strong>isopropyl alcohol</strong> and wipe each blade.</li>
      <li>If dust is severe (<em>e.g.</em>, after many hours in a dusty room), remove the fan housing for a thorough clean.</li>
    </ol>
    <div class="alert alert-info">
      💡 Check that all fans spin freely after cleaning. A stuck fan can cause heat-creep and clogs.
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- ═══ 9. SPRING STEEL BUILD PLATE ═══ -->
<section>
  <div class="card">
    <h2>9. Spring Steel Sheet (Build Plate) <span class="badge">Every print</span></h2>
    <p>Oils from your fingertips weaken bed adhesion. A clean sheet is the #1 fix for first-layer problems.</p>
    <ol>
      <li>Remove the spring steel sheet from the magnetic bed.</li>
      <li>Wash with <strong>warm water + dish soap</strong>, then rinse thoroughly. <em>Or</em> wipe with isopropyl alcohol after every print.</li>
      <li>For stubborn residue (glue stick, PETG adhesion), wash with soap and water — alcohol alone won’t dissolve water-soluble glue.</li>
      <li>Dry completely before re-seating on the bed.</li>
    </ol>
    <div class="alert alert-warn">
      🖐️ Handle the sheet by the edges only. Avoid touching the textured surface.
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- ═══ BONUS ═══ -->
<section>
  <div class="card">
    <h2>🔧 Bonus — General Good Practices</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Keep the enclosure clean.</strong> Wipe down interior walls and the glass door monthly — airborne particles land on prints.</li>
      <li><strong>Check belts (if accessible).</strong> Pluck the X/Y belts — they should sound like a low guitar note. Too loose → ghosting; too tight → bearing wear.</li>
      <li><strong>Check the PTFE tube.</strong> If the Bowden tube (if used) shows scorch marks at the hotend end, trim 5–10 mm or replace it.</li>
      <li><strong>Store filament properly.</strong> Dry filament = fewer clogs and better surface finish. Use a dry box for hygroscopic materials (PETG, TPU, Nylon).</li>
      <li><strong>Run a PID tune</strong> if you see temperature fluctuations during prints (firmware menu or via G-code).</li>
      <li><strong>Log your maintenance.</strong> Jot down what you did and when — it helps diagnose issues later.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- ═══ CHECKLIST ═══ -->
<section>
  <div class="card">
    <h2>📋 Quick-Check Walkaround (Pre-Print)</h2>
    <ul class="checklist">
      <li class="done">Spring steel sheet is clean and seated flat.</li>
      <li>No debris on the PEI/textured surface.</li>
      <li>Filament spool turns freely; no tangles.</li>
      <li>Nozzle tip is clean (wipe with a brass brush or tissue while hot if needed).</li>
      <li>Z-screw and Y-rods are clean and lightly lubricated.</li>
      <li>Fans spin up correctly on startup.</li>
      <li>Silicone sock is seated and intact.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</section>

<footer>
  <p>Compiled from the <a href="https://wiki.anycubic.com/en/fdm-3d-printer/kobra-s1-combo/maintenance-recommendations" target="_blank">Anycubic Kobra S1 Maintenance Wiki</a> + general FDM best practices.</p>
  <p>Last updated June 2026. Always consult the official wiki for model-specific updates.</p>
</footer>

</div>
</body>
</html>"}

